Short answer:

❌ It’s NOT true that method_missing is not used.
✅ But define_method is preferred in most predictable cases.

Now I’ll explain clearly.

First Understand The Real Difference
🔹 method_missing

Used when:

👉 You do NOT know the method names in advance
👉 You want to catch any unknown method dynamically

It runs every time a missing method is called.

🔹 define_method

Used when:

👉 You DO know the pattern of methods
👉 You can generate them in advance

It defines the method once, and Ruby finds it normally afterward.

🚀 Why define_method Is Preferred Most of the Time

Because:

Faster (no fallback logic every time)

Cleaner

Works automatically with respond_to?

Easier to debug

More maintainable

So in modern Ruby code:

✔ Prefer define_method when possible
✔ Use method_missing only when necessary

🧠 When Is method_missing Still Used?

It is still used in:

DSLs (Domain Specific Languages)

Highly dynamic APIs

Proxy objects

Delegators

Some internal framework magic

For example, Rails earlier versions used method_missing heavily for dynamic finders.

In modern Rails, many things are now generated using dynamic method definition instead (better performance).

🎯 What Interviewer Wants to Hear

If interviewer asks:

“Is method_missing still used?”

Best answer:

Yes, but carefully. When method names are predictable, I prefer define_method because it improves performance and maintainability. method_missing is useful for highly dynamic behavior or DSLs, but it should be used with caution and paired with respond_to_missing?.

That answer shows:

✔ You understand tradeoffs
✔ You’re not blindly using magic
✔ You care about performance

🔥 Very Important

Senior engineers don’t avoid method_missing.

They avoid abusing it.

🧠 Super Simple Rule To Remember

If you can generate methods beforehand → use define_method
If you must handle completely unknown method names → use method_missing

